Otago, Long Beach, 30 December 1998, G. S. Stone s.n., (AK 239841); Otago, Long Beach, 25 Jun 1997, D. Nelson s.n. &amp; J. Barkla, (CHR 518601); Otago, Long Beach, 13 July 2009, P. B. Heen 
<pageBreakToken id="A1C2313502807C4E438C39EE3A7DF4EF" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" start="start">an</pageBreakToken>
s.n., (CHR 609779);Otago,Long Beach, 14 July 2009, P. B. Heenan s.n., (CHR 609780); Tomahawk Beach, 4 February [1920?], B. C. Aston s.n., (WELT SP027651, WELT SP052362); Tavora Reserve, 13 July 2009, P. B. Heenan s.n., (CHR 609786-609789);Otago Peninsula,Green Island, January 1955, R. A.. Falla s.n., (WELT SP038744); Otago Peninsula, Green Island, January 1957, M. E. Gillham s.n., (CHR 111452); Otago Peninsula, Green Island, 6 July 1983, P. N. Johnson 70, (CHR 404351); Otago Peninsula, Green Island, 27 March 1989, P. N. Johnson 823, (AK 185642, CHR 461272); Otago Peninsula, Green Island, 12 February 1999, G. Loh s.n., (AK 238646); Solander Island, 10 November 1973, P. N. Johnson s.n., (CHR 253066). 
<emphasis id="992B9D6FACFB8DE857C0836D0390BCD7" bold="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">New Zealand (Stewart Island/Rakiura):</emphasis>
Halfmoon Bay, Mill Bay, 4 February 1963, P. Hynes s.n., (AK 92212); Womans Island, January 1976, P. N. Johnson s.n., (CHR 261892); Herekopare Island, 20 May 1959, E. A. Willa s.n., (WELT SP050477, AK 249215); Herekopare Island, 4 January 2010, P. B. Heenan s.n, (CHR 609808-609810); Mutton Bird (Titi) Islands, Big Moggy Islands, December 2002, B. D. Rance s.n., (AK 293254). 
<emphasis id="EAA40BD9B3CE51B71D08AD7B2BBF9E2C" bold="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Cultivated (New Zealand):</emphasis>
Lincoln, ex Herekopare Island, 2 Feb 1980, H. D. Wilson 798-314, (CHR 368843); Lincoln, ex Long Beach, Landcare Research experimental nursery, 10 July 2008, P. B. Heenan s.n., (CHR 609803).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B70C57AAC03D17DD2631E8C53D85C2C4" lastPageId="48" lastPageNumber="49" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="356F75B98D097DAFDD5B9B1B777F233A" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4D8885891656ADA7FD22A89225CCD998" lastPageId="48" lastPageNumber="49" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="16C9C80E977C63913A6C4BA5A65C043D" bold="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
(
<figureCitation id="E4110584475AE846D80C103F4ED007F3" captionStart="Figure 44" captionStartId="F44" captionText="Figure 44. Distribution of Lepidium flexicaule (New Zealand distribution shown only), Lepidium juvencum, Lepidium limenophylax, Lepidium naufragorum and Lepidium obtusatum." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10782" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Fig. 44</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Endemic. New Zealand. South and Stewart Island/Rakiura. Known from Otago and islands off the coast of Stewart Island/Rakiura 
<taxonomicName id="5E72AE67E3E44C124D5FD0029412E3DE" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juvencum">
<emphasis id="988E0AD691E18990F5E758D7DCD52574" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Lepidium juvencum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is currently known from just three locations: Long Beach and Green Island (Otago 
<pageBreakToken id="7C793B42FC60B649B5134C36AF11C6BE" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" start="start">Peninsula</pageBreakToken>
) and Herekopare Island (east of Stewart Island/Rakiura). However, it is also probably present on some of the south-western Titi Island (south-west of Stewart Island/Rakiura) (B.D. Rance pers. comm.) and it is still likely to occur elsewhere, especially on rat free islands in the vicinity of Stewart Island, as is evidenced by specimens previously col 
<pageBreakToken id="F35F38FB1CCA9D0F3658F69152C823C3" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" start="start">lected</pageBreakToken>
from Womans (CHR 261892) and Solander (CHR 253066) islands in the 1960s and 1970s.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C0D445D4602ACB21B6E7F8E4C697B13B" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="recognition">
<paragraph id="21821FDEF6EC369B399E92574CEB93F0" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Recognition.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F02E093703C83878816835689AE247FC" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<taxonomicName id="050DF6C37D0128B8DF4DDA6FBDDD68CB" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juvencum">
<emphasis id="4C166A945C2FE36B719A3D159794BDB6" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Lepidium juvencum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by open, sprawling, straggling growth habit, and the stems are often trailing on the ground (
<figureCitation id="E7FA98C89A99F2DDA7A216F835D3CD19" captionStart="Figure 46" captionStartId="F46" captionText="Figure 46. Young plant of Lepidium juvencum growing with Poa astonii near shearwater burrows." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10784" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Figs 46</figureCitation>
<figureCitation id="EAB125BFD165BF2BC6DF2B777D434A00" captionStart="Figure 47" captionStartId="F47" captionText="Figure 47. Flowering stem of Lepidium juvencum showing multiple inflorescences and trailing growth habit. Scale bar = 20 mm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10785" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">, 47</figureCitation>
). The leaves are elliptic, elliptic-oblanceolate, obovate to elliptic-obovate, and have attenuate bases; the marginal teeth are usually small and are mostly confined to the distal third of the leaf (
<figureCitation id="625722C0229088A2DCD8F62940DC8211" captionStart="Figure 48" captionStartId="F48" captionText="Figure 48. (From left to right) basal-, mid- and upper-stem leaves of Lepidium juvencum. Scale bar = 20 mm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10786" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 48</figureCitation>
). The silicles are most like 
<taxonomicName id="29BA440B954163B319DCCFC6BE9A3A64" authorityName="G. Forst. ex Sparrm., Nova Acta Soc. Sc. Upsal. iii, 193" authorityYear="1780" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oleraceum">
<emphasis id="E3CCEE4A168507B103210E7CD9E2C275" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Lepidium oleraceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differ by possessing a rounded, slightly notched apex (
<figureCitation id="604D6106C2C57440B842B78B15BFA884" captionStart="Figure 49" captionStartId="F49" captionText="Figure 49. (A) Mature silicle of Lepidium juvencum; (B) close up of silicle apex showing slight notch. AK 297694. Scale bars = 1 mm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10787" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 49</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="82BD055F742299A8BE329F5A87AD6112" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="0B21306B1FD805421C4AAD515A25351E" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1131BAA902A40353C87B51C3DDC4D053" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<taxonomicName id="3ECA6A522B0157BCD06C788E935CF32C" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juvencum">
<emphasis id="1902E0D78FDD79BDFD0C4BA0369497F5" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Lepidium juvencum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
grows in open and often disturbed sites on sandy soil. At Long Beach it grows on stabilised sand at the base of a cliff immediately behind the beach, and at Herekopere Island it occurred on a steep coastal bank comprising sandy loam. On Kaimohu Island, in the south-western Titi group, what is probably 
<taxonomicName id="E851D2C1772F3268AB82CAC3E5EBB399" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juvencum">
<emphasis id="2146544F96202459EC6528DEF98E29B8" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Lepidium juvencum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been recorded growing with 
<taxonomicName id="FA5902FF6EFB81FDF589B82C6B648244" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="limenophylax">
<emphasis id="09B406EED484422E2BB303742457E967" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Lepidium limenophylax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the margins of coastal scrub. 
<taxonomicName id="E67CBBA1EC401C2DF5D6940CB42504D8" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juvencum">
<emphasis id="CE5791126E89F074AF981C277A8A31B7" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Lepidium juvencum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has also been established and is self-seeding at the Yellow-eyed Penguin Trust revegetation project at Tavora Reserve (near Palmerston, North Otago). Here it grows among 
<taxonomicName id="1A130CDB364C74069A551C48824A37E6" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Euphorbia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Geraniales" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="glauca">
<emphasis id="2E5F443882FC1DFAD4FD226D6E9AD390" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Euphorbia glauca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
G.Forst. and 
<taxonomicName id="DF7CE6CCF561AF8581506209B7601158" authorityName="Muasya &amp; de Lange" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="A. Rich." class="Liliopsida" family="Cyperaceae" genus="Ficinia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="spiralis">
<emphasis id="86FDF78BAD47157CA05F17B0EC340293" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Ficinia spiralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(A.Rich.) Muasya et de Lange on sand dunes at the back of the beach.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="654A5928BF6D7DC2A054CE86C187C0C5" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="conservation status">
<paragraph id="52DD90FB4F61998A4AFD58CC5980F082" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Conservation Status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="98285917259AEC9ECC63EAE42871B63C" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<taxonomicName id="CB3782F7A46C69B6F91488373088A1EF" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juvencum">
<emphasis id="53713E07BE952D17ABD390EE50CA68BE" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Lepidium juvencum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is presently known from three wild localities, and, while the number of plants at these localities is not known with certainty, it is estimated that there are &lt;100 in total. It is also acknowledged that 
<taxonomicName id="F3BA5B6162CD7E26BA49EA820B16D094" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juvencum">
<emphasis id="9A503094739EB6EAF89DE2A2BE4733A5" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Lepidium juvencum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is likely to be more widespread, especially in the vicinity of Stewart Island/Rakiura, and further field surveys are required. Recruitment is likely to be sporadic, and the small and sparse populations are especially vulnerable to stochastic events, such as storm surges, that could erode its habitat. Based on our current knowledge of this species and using the New Zealand Threat Classification System (
<bibRefCitation id="5FC5265E538ECA65255A0E640D2E57CE" author="Townsend, AJ" journalOrPublisher="Bioinformatics" pageId="116" pageNumber="117" refId="B86" refString="Townsend, AJ, de Lange, PJ, Norton, DA, Molloy, J, Miskelly, C, Duffy, C, 2008. The New Zealand Threat Classification System manual. Department of Conservation: Wellington. http://www.doc.govt.nz/publications/conservation/nz-threat-classification-system/nz-threat-classification-system-manual-2008/." title="The New Zealand Threat Classification System manual. Department of Conservation: Wellington. http: // www. doc. govt. nz / publications / conservation / nz-threat-classification-system / nz-threat-classification-system-manual- 2008 /" year="2008">Townsend et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName id="3823FE8CE31A86D16FD597DD1F8ED134" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juvencum">
<emphasis id="189515F6707DADF3CCDFDF5F79E6468B" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Lepidium juvencum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
qualifies as 'Threatened/Nationally 
<normalizedToken id="0B9CF7025CFE699B11107C98E8475E6A" originalValue="Critical’">Critical'</normalizedToken>
(either criterion A(1) or A(3) of 
<bibRefCitation id="3E3C392D3A3978586087B405E20989ED" author="Townsend, AJ" journalOrPublisher="Bioinformatics" pageId="116" pageNumber="117" refId="B86" refString="Townsend, AJ, de Lange, PJ, Norton, DA, Molloy, J, Miskelly, C, Duffy, C, 2008. The New Zealand Threat Classification System manual. Department of Conservation: Wellington. http://www.doc.govt.nz/publications/conservation/nz-threat-classification-system/nz-threat-classification-system-manual-2008/." title="The New Zealand Threat Classification System manual. Department of Conservation: Wellington. http: // www. doc. govt. nz / publications / conservation / nz-threat-classification-system / nz-threat-classification-system-manual- 2008 /" year="2008">Townsend et al. (2008)</bibRefCitation>
applies). We recommend appending the qualifiers, 
<normalizedToken id="8671EEDCAF648D13E91DD97DAE9B8D65" originalValue="‘CD’">'CD'</normalizedToken>
(Conservation Dependent - because the species has been deliberately established at Tavora Reserve, where it is actively managed), 
<normalizedToken id="895C964A44315FFADE094F25BBD7F92D" originalValue="‘DP’">'DP'</normalizedToken>
(Data Poor - to reflect uncertainty over its distribution), and 
<normalizedToken id="CCD47787D6C5DED0AD1E32850BDF63F0" originalValue="‘RR’">'RR'</normalizedToken>
(Range Restricted - because it is naturally confined to a geographically small part of the New Zealand Botanical Region).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
